V'''Nigel Warburton''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|w|\u0254r|b|\u0259r|t|\u0259n}}; born 1962) is a British [[philosopher]]. He is best known as a populariser of philosophy, having written a number of books in the genre, but he has also written academic works in [[aesthetics]] and [[applied ethics]].<ref>Baggini, Julian &  Jeremy Stangroom (eds.) ''New British Philosophy'', p. 272. Routledge, 2002. ISBN 0-415-24346-7.</ref>\u000a\u000a==Education==\u000aWarburton received a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] from the [[University of Bristol]] and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] from [[Darwin College, Cambridge]], and was a lecturer at the [[University of Nottingham]] before joining the Department of Philosophy at [[the Open University]] in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|title=Faculty of Arts: Department of Philosophy|publisher=Open University|url=http://www.open.ac.uk/Arts/philos/warburton.htm|accessdate=2007-09-04}}</ref> In May 2013, he resigned from the position of Senior Lecturer at the Open University.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=The Philosophers Magazine|title=Nigel Warburton, virtual philosopher|url=http://philosophypress.co.uk/?p=1159|accessdate=2013-06-10}}</ref>\u000a\u000a==Career==\u000aHe is the author of a number of introductory Philosophy books, including the bestselling ''Philosophy: The Basics'' (4th ed.), ''Philosophy: The Classics'' (4th ed.), and ''Thinking from A to Z'' (3rd ed.); he also edited ''Philosophy: Basic Readings'' (2nd ed.) and was the co-author of ''Reading Political Philosophy: Machiavelli to Mill''. He has written extensively about photography, particularly about [[Bill Brandt]], and wrote a biography of the modernist architect [[Ern\u0151 Goldfinger]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Nigel Warburton CV at PFD|publisher=PFD Group Ltd|url=http://www.pfd.co.uk/clients/warburtn/b-aut.html|accessdate=2007-09-04 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071024175008/http://www.pfd.co.uk/clients/warburtn/b-aut.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-10-24}}</ref> He regularly teaches courses on philosophy and art at [[Tate Modern]] and writes a monthly column "Everyday Philosophy" for ''Prospect'' magazine.\u000a\u000aHe runs a philosophy [[weblog]] ''Virtual Philosopher''<ref>http://www.virtualphilosopher.org</ref> and with [[David Edmonds (philosopher)|David Edmonds]] regularly podcasts interviews with top philosophers on a range of subjects at ''[[Philosophy Bites]]''.<ref>http://www.philosophybites.com</ref> He also podcasts chapters from his book ''Philosophy: The Classics''.<ref>http://www.philclassics.libsyn.com</ref>\u000a\u000a== Partial bibliography ==\u000a*''Philosophy: The Basics'' (4th ed.) ISBN 978-0-415-32773-2\u000a*''Philosophy: The Classics'' (4th ed.) ISBN 978-0-415-53466-6\u000a*''Thinking from A to Z'' (3rd ed.) ISBN 978-0-415-43371-6\u000a*''The Art Question''\u000a*''Ernö Goldfinger: The Life of An Architect''\u000a*''Free Speech: A Very Short Introduction'' ISBN 978-0-19-923235-2\u000a*''Philosophy Bites'' (co-edited with David Edmonds) ISBN 978-0-19-957632-6; ''Philosophy Bites. 25 Philosophen sprechen über 25 große Themen'' (translated by Holger Hanowell), Reclam 2013\u000a* ''Philosophy Bites Back'' (co-edited with David Edmonds) ISBN 978-0-19-969300-9; ''Auf den Schultern von Riesen. 27 Philosophen sprechen über ihre Lieblingsphilosophen'' (translated by Holger Hanowell), Reclam 2015\u000a*''A Little History of Philosophy'' ISBN 978-0-300-15208-1\u000a\u000a== References ==\u000a{{reflist|2}}\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a{{multicol}}\u000a*{{wikiquote-inline}}\u000a*[http://www.nigelwarburton.com Official site]\u000a*[http://www.philosophybites.com ''Philosophy Bites'' podcast]\u000a*[http://www.open2.net/ethicsbites/ ''Ethics Bites'' podcast]\u000a{{multicol-break}}\u000a*[http://media.podcasts.ox.ac.uk/oucs/oxonian_interviews/warburtonedmonds_interview.mp3 Nigel Warburton and David Edmonds on Podcasting at ''Oxonians'']\u000a*[http://www.virtualphilosopher.org ''Virtual Philosopher'' weblog]\u000a*[http://www.artandallusion.com ''Art and Allusion'' weblog]\u000a*[http://www.vsi-free-speech.com ''Free Speech'' weblog]\u000a{{multicol-end}}\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Warburton, Nigel}}\u000a[[Category:1962 births]]\u000a[[Category:Living people]]\u000a[[Category:Academics of the Open University]]\u000a[[Category:English book editors]]\u000a[[Category:British political philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Philosophy writers]]\u000a[[Category:Alumni of Darwin College, Cambridge]]\u000a[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bristol]]\u000a[[Category:Academics of the University of Nottingham]]\u000a[[Category:Historians of philosophy]]
